x4freetext: K-400 Neutron Generator
The neutrons were produced with an effective
deuteron beam energy of 134 keV, and a beam current
of 240 uA.
NaBr powder (99.99% pure, 0.6-0.9 g) was placed
inside a polymethyl methacrylate sample box. Four
samples with a diameter of 20 mm and eight monitors
with the same diameter were prepared for the
irradiation. The thicknesses of the four NaBr samples
A low-background high-purity germanium (HPGe)
detector equipped with an energy resolution of 1.69 keV
(FWHM) at 1.332 MeV for 60Co and a relative
efficiency of about 68% (ORTEC, model GEM 60P, crystal
length of 72.3 mm, crystal diameter of 70.1 mm) was
used to measure the radioactivity. The detection
efficiency of the HPGe detector was obtained using
the 25 gamma lines of the standard sources 133Ba,
137Cs, 152Eu, and 226Ra.
The irradiation of the samples was carried
out for approximately two hours with a neutron yield
4 to 5 E10 n/s in the 4 Pi solid angle. Cooling time
is 12 min and measuring time is 118.6 s for the peaks
of interest are 613.7, 616.3, and 694.9 keV. Cooling
time is 52 min and measuring time is 18.2 min for the
peaks of interest are 103.01 keV, 559.1 keV, 616.3
keV, and 694.9 keV.
The coincidence-summation effect of cascade
gamma-rays produced by the nuclide, the self-
absorption of the gamma-rays, the attenuation of
gamma-rays in polymethyl methacrylate, and the
specimen counting geometries.
